,"1390–1422":"1390–1422","1367–1406":"1367–1406","1400–1453":"1400–1453","1350–1410":"1350–1410","1352–1409":"1352–1409","Aft 10 February 1443":"na 10 februari 1443","13 December 1410":"13 december 1410","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Abt 1406":"circa 1406","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","about 1409":"circa 1409","1400":"1400","1367":"1367","1422":"1422","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","1453":"1453","1409":"1409","Abt 1380":"circa 1380","1406":"1406","Fisherwick, Staffordshire, England":"Fisherwick, Staffordshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Boston, Lincolnshire, England":"Boston, Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1380–Aft 10 February 1443":"about 1380–after 10 February 1443","1380–1443":"1380–1443","1390–1422":"1390–1422","1367–1406":"1367–1406","1400–1453":"1400–1453","1350–1410":"1350–1410","1352–1409":"1352–1409","Aft 10 February 1443":"after 10 February 1443","13 December 1410":"13 December 1410","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Abt 1406":"about 1406","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","about 1409":"about 1409","1400":"1400","1367":"1367","1422":"1422","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","1453":"1453","1409":"1409","Abt 1380":"about 1380","1406":"1406","Fisherwick, Staffordshire, England":"Fisherwick, Staffordshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Boston, Lincolnshire, England":"Boston, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rochford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Niall.","English: variant of   Ratchford  .","Irish: of Norman origin, probably brought to Ireland by the Normans after 1171, when Henry II acquired Dublin. However, it is not known if it was an English name (see   Ratchford  ), or a Norman equivalent of the French name   Rochefort  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rockford","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Rochford   or   Ratchford  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Rachford","meanings":["English:","variant of   Rochford  .","variant of<b>Rackford</b>, a habitational name from Rackenford in Devon,recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Racheneforda</i>, which Millsinterprets as ‘ford suitable for riding, by a stretch of river’."]},{"name":"Ratchford","meanings":["habitational name from Rochford (Worcestershire), from Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’ (genitive <i>ræcces</i>) + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","habitational name from Rochford (Essex). Early forms of the name ending in <i>Ro-</i> suggest that the placename derives from Old English <i>hrōc</i> ‘rook’ or the Old English personal name <i>Hrōc(a)</i> + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, but the 13th century forms in <i>Ra-</i> and <i>Re-</i> suggest that the first element is Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’.","English:"]},{"name":"Rotchford","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin.","Irish and English: variant of   Rochford  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Rochford was born about 1380, her father, John Rochford, was 32 and her mother, Alice Hastings, was 30. She had at least 1 son with Frederick Tilney Sheriff of Cambrid